2026-04-09 | Intersection of Two Sorted Arrays (Distinct Elements)

	Question
Return intersection of both arrays.

	Approach
1.	Use two pointers:
		i for array a  
		j for array b  

2.	Traverse both arrays:
		- If a[i] == b[j]:
				add to result (if not already added)  
				move both pointers  
		- If a[i] < b[j]:
				move i  
		- Else:
				move j  

3.	Skip duplicates:
		ensure each element is added once  

	Time Complexity
	O(n + m)

	Space Complexity
	O(1) (excluding output)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> intersection(vector<int>& a, vector<int>& b) {

        int i = 0, j = 0;
        int n = a.size(), m = b.size();

        vector<int> ans;

        while(i < n && j < m){

            if(a[i] == b[j]){

                if(ans.empty() || ans.back() != a[i])
                    ans.push_back(a[i]);

                i++;
                j++;
            }
            else if(a[i] < b[j]){
                i++;
            }
            else{
                j++;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Since arrays are sorted:
we can efficiently find intersection using **two pointers**.  

Handling duplicates carefully ensures:
		result contains only **distinct common elements**.
